[normal]5)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]TV and [bold]digital[bold] developments[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The challenges in reaching global audiences are intensifying. Global state funded and 
[normal]commercial players are investing (
[normal]the BBC
[normal] estimate
[normal]s
[normal] CCTV’s funding has increased by $2bn per annum, and competitors including CNN and New York Times have a growing multi-lingual portfolio). At a local and regional level, news provision is 
[normal]rapidly increasin
[normal]g; Afghanistan, for example, now has 80 terrestrial TV stations and over 175 radio stations. Digital developments are accelerating this change. Short
[normal] 
[normal]wave listening continues to decline, with some of 
[normal]BBC WS’s
[normal] largest audiences in Nigeria and Burma
[normal] facing p
[normal]ressure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For the time being, radio is still 
[normal]the W
[normal]orld 
[normal]S
[normal]ervice
[normal]’s
[normal] largest platform and the most cost-effective form of distribution, but as short
[normal] 
[normal]wave becomes less relevant to most audiences, 
[normal]the BBC must offer
[normal] a greater multiplatform presence.  
[normal]Investment
[normal] in new TV programming
[normal] and digital output is a key part of 
[normal]World Service
[normal]’s
[normal] strategy. Four new language TV bulletins were launched this year, and are now on air:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Focus on Africa: [bold]Launched on both BBC W
[normal]orld News and on 11 partner TV s
[normal]tations in 
[normal]eight
[normal] countries. This programme is an extension of 
[normal]BBC Africa’s
[normal] strong radio brand into television and represents 
[normal]a 
[normal]unique partnership with 
[normal]BBC World News. 
[normal]Reporting expertise is provided by existing BBC Africa reporters in Africa, complimented by the poo
[normal]l of N
[normal]ewsgathering staff on the 
[normal]continent. This 
[normal]was 
[normal]the first stage in Global News’ investment in new content and programming aimed at reaching different audiences around the world who are changing the way they consume their news. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Diira Ya Dunia: [bold]Launched in 
[normal]August, a 30 minute bulletin aimed at Swahili speaking audiences in East and Central Africa, which airs in Tanzania and Kenya on partner TV stations.
[normal] 
[normal] A
[normal] number of
[normal] new partners in DRC and Rwanda 
[normal]have been added 
[normal]enabling BBC WS to expand its reach in Africa.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Global India: [bold]A weekly 30-minute magazine-style show from the Hindi service launched in November on five Hindi news channels on the ETV network in India, at prime time. Each programme gets three playouts on all five channels.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Sairbeen (Panorama): [bold]A th
[normal]rice weekly one-hour TV programme from the Urdu service of regional and global news for audiences in Pakistan launched in February 2013. The programme was increased to five times a week in the run up to Pakistani elections.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Although audience performance d
[normal]ata
[normal] is not yet available
[normal], several of 
[normal]the
[normal] TV partners have signed-up to the programmes for another year on the same or improved commercial terms. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Feedback from Star TV on 
[normal]Diira Ya Dunia
[normal] has been especially positive, with the CEO keen to renew the contract. In addition, in Kenya reaction on social media to editions of 
[normal]Focus On Africa
[normal] and 
[normal]Diira Ya Dunia
[normal] 
[normal]has been extensive 
[normal]and very positive.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]World Service Digital[bold]:[bold]This year, the last seven
[normal] 
[normal]language 
[normal]websites 
[normal]were
[normal] updated in accordance with the new and improved visual and presentation style, in line with the ‘feel and look’ of the rest of the BBC sites. 11 Nokia Apps, 5 iOS Apps, and 4 Andr
[normal]oid apps have now been released
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Several World Service websites have now been converted to responsive design including Indonesia, Hausa, Arabic, Vietnamese, Turkish¸ Russian, Hindi, Afrique, Mundo, Brasil and Persian with the conversion of many more languages in progress. Responsive desig
[normal]n is a technology that optimises the mobile browser according to the device used – adjusting the layout to the screen size and connectivity. It is especially helpful for the language services, given the diverse markets they serve and the huge array of diff
[normal]erent phones and technical standards in those markets. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As mentioned in the 
[normal]Audience Figures
[normal] section, these developments have contributed to a 16% increase in World Service digital audience globally.  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Media freedom [bold]update[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Media freedom issues continue 
[normal]to affect the BBC’s ability to reach its audiences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Many of these issues were 
[normal]described in detail
[normal] in BBC World Service’s written evidence submitted to the FAC’
[normal]s Human Rights inquiry.  This is a
[normal] brief summary of 
[normal]the 
[normal]issues 
[normal]BBC WS 
[normal]has faced 
[normal]this year
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Journalists[bold]’[bold] s[bold]afety:[bold]The BBC has been extremely concerned about the safety of its journalists in several parts of the world. Syria has continued to be a dangerous place to report and violence and pressures on media in Egypt have made it a difficult place t
[normal]o work as a journalist. BBC reporter 
[normal]Mohammed Moalimu, 
[normal]came close to death in Somalia when in July an al-Shabab suicide bomber detonated his explosives just as Moalimu was driving past.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] He was wounded by shrapnel in his shoulder.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But it is not just in c
[normal]onflict zones that journalists’ safety is being threatened. A BBC Tamil reporter, Ponnaiah Manikavasagam, was questioned for hours by anti-terrorist police in Sri Lanka over his phone conversations with two Tamil prisoners. He was not allowed a lawyer duri
[normal]ng the interview. BBC WS raised its concern and expressed confidence that all his activities were carried out in pursuit of normal journalistic duties. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In Turkey, during Gezi
[normal] Park protests, Turkish authorities launched a campaign of intimidation against BBC Turkish reporter, Selin Girit. She had been deployed to Istanbul to cover the protests both for Turkish and English outlets. The mayor of Ankara launched a campaign against
[normal] Selin on Twitter, resulting in a large number of threatening messages being sent to her. In a statement, the BBC called on the Turkish 
[normal]authorities not to intimidate its reporter and to use the established procedures if they have any complaints about BBC o
[normal]utput. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In Iran, security authorities have continued harassing BBC Persian staff and their families. In the weeks leading to the Iranian presidential election in June, the incidents of harassment increased and the media campaign against BBC Persian staff
[normal] intensified. Although after the election the harassment stopped for a while, in recent weeks a new wave of intimidation of families has started again. Families of several members of staff have been threatened to stop their relatives working for the BBC. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To highlight the importance of journalists’ safety and the issue of impunity, the BBC is organising a conference next year. It is a follow-up to the conference it co-hosted last October. The conference will bring together senior journalists, NGOs and 
[normal]representatives from UN’s relevant bodies and governments
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It will examine what international legal bodies could do to prosecute those who are responsible for attacking and intimidating journalists.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Jamming in China:[bold]The jamming of BBC English short wa
[normal]ve services by China has occurred since February this year and also affects reception of the service in many other Asian countries.  
[normal]Access to the BBC Chinese (Mandarin) website has been completely blocked since its launch in 1999.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBC strongly cond
[normal]emns
[normal] this action, but
[normal] despite 
[normal]representations made to the Chinese Ambassador, the regulator, and the Director Global News raising the issue in meetings duri
[normal]ng his recent visit to China, the BBC
[normal] has not received a response
[normal] from the Chinese authorities
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Broadcasts suspended in Sri Lanka:[bold]BBC WS suspended its broadcasts on SLBC (the Sri Lankan Broadcasting Corporation) following continued interruption and interference of BBC Tamil programming.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Despite requests for discussion about any complaints that SLBC
[normal] might have had about any specific output, the issue has not been resolved.  The BBC took similar action in 2009 when its services were also disrupted.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Audiences in Sri Lanka can continue to listen to th
[normal]e BBC on short wave and via 
[normal]online services
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]TV par[bold]tnership suspended in [bold]Turkey:[bold]Following the start of protests in Turkey in June the Turkish service took the decision to suspend its TV partnership with NTV in Turkey, after NTV interfered with its broadcasting. 
[normal]BBC Turkish subsequently relaunched its digi
[normal]tal offer with a greater emphasis on mobile, video and social news, and has seen its traffic soar more than 350% in one year alone with nearly 90% of the audience coming from within Turkey.
[normal]Progress in [bold]Burma:[bold]There were uplifting developments in Burma
[normal]/Myanmar
[normal] [bold]where the government has 
[normal]strictly
[normal] controlled  the media over a number of years. 
[normal]For the past nine months BBC Media Action has been helping the state broadcaster - MRTV - to achieve its declared aim of evolving into a public service broadcaster by 
[normal]January 2015. As a result of this support MRTV now has its first prime-time politics programme to feature interviews with members of all the parties represented in Parliament, a new radio current affairs programmes featuring differing points of view and an
[normal] emerging newsgathering structure that is more independent than anything the country has known in the past few decades .
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition a youth programme is broadcast on the BBC's Burmese Service 
[normal]that informs audiences about governance issues and encourages 
[normal]discussion and participation and developing other projects to improve livelihoods, health and resilience to natural disasters. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There have
[normal] also
[normal] been
[normal] a number of distribution break
[normal]throughs with BBC TV channels including BBC World News now available on the 
[normal]SkyNet 
[normal]TV platform in Burma
[normal],
[normal] a 
[normal]rebroadcasting deal 
[normal]with 
[normal]Padamyar FM
[normal] and another one with key FM station 
[normal]Shwe
[normal] which covers 98% of the country in the pipeline.  In addition, t
[normal]he
[normal] Burmese service became the first international broadcaster on the mobile platfor
[normal]m in Burma through the launch of daily audio bulletins, as well as SMS bulletins. 
