[normal]8)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Transfer to the licence fee[bold]&#xa0;[bold]BBC WS is now looki
[normal]ng ahead to more stable funding and the benefits of greater integration with BBC News, as a result of the transfer to the licence fee on 1 April 2014. It will join BBC Monitoring which has been funded by the licence fee since 1 April 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On 25 June 2013
[normal] the BBC Trust published its draft Operating Licence for the World Service, 
[normal]setting out its strategy for World Service in the licence fee, 
[normal]for public consultation. Further context was provided in the accompanying Position Paper “
[normal]BBC World Service – A licen
[normal]ce fee funded service
[normal]”.
[normal] The Trust is currently assessing the feedback received during the consultation and will publish its responses in due course. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The draft Operating Licence defines the Objectives, Priorities and Targets (as agreed with the Foreign 
[normal]Secretary), scope of services, funding and performance measurement of the World Service under the licence fee. Any significant change to the Licence will require the approval of the BBC Trust.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Policy Position paper makes it clear that the World Servic
[normal]e 
[normal]will 
[normal]be an integral part of the BBC News operation, which provides independent and impartial news and analysis to UK and global audiences. Most importantly, the paper states that the Trust will ensure that the distinctive service offered by the World Ser
[normal]vice is protected, and enhanced. The impact of the World Service will not be diminished as a result of an administrative change in funding. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Trust also announced its plan to increase funding for World Service to £245m in 2014/15 (in the 2013/14 financ
[normal]ial year the total grant from the UK Government for World Service is £238.5m). Under the terms of the Operating Licence, any planned or actual change in the licence fee-funded content and distribution budget of more than 
[normal]10% in real value will be regarded 
[normal]as a significant change and require approval from the BBC Trust. The Trust also proposed that in addition to its licence fee budget, World Service should seek non-licence fee sources of funding (including commercial funding) where appropriate and within re
[normal]gulatory requirements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On 8 October 2013 the Director-General of the BBC shared his ambition for the BBC. Reflecting the importance and value of the World Service, the announcements included an ambition to double the BBC’s global audience by 2022 from 250
[normal] million users a week to 500 million.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Within the BBC Executive, the ‘1414 Programme’ has been created to ensure that all aspects of the transition of the World Service to licence fee funding are addressed. The programme is considering ways of integrating the World Service to ensure maximum val
[normal]ue for licence fee payers and putting a future strategy in place which offers the best possible service to global audiences. The programme is also considering appropriate accountability and regulatory regimes, working with Government where necessary. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thi
[normal]s programme is progressing to schedule. James Harding, Director News and Current Affairs, assumed the role of Executive Sponsor from September 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
